    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThere seems to be no good reason other than historical that the value of `updatetime` is used for both time to write to swap file as well as time to trigger `CursorHold` autocommand event. The default of 4000 ms seems far too high for `CursorHold` and some plugins make use as low as 100 ms for the event, but that would also be too low for writing to swap. \n\n[FixCursorHold.nvim](https://github.com/antoinemadec/fixcursorhold.nvim) plugin addresses this issue (the README suggests the plugin is redundant after a performance issue was fixed in core but [that only addresses one of the issues](https://github.com/antoinemadec/FixCursorHold.nvim/issues/13).  \n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`updatetime` should only be associated with one of these events and an option for the other.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Just thinking out loud: `CursorHold` is still relevant because it indicates \"user idle\", that's the main difference vs timers (`timer_start()`).\n\nI've long wanted to introduce a flavor of `CursorHold` called `UserIdle` or `CursorIdle` which allows the subscriber to say what \"intervals\" they are interested in, something like this:\n\n    :autocmd UserIdle 100 :echo localtime()\n\nand that would fire every 100ms. Or we could add this to the existing `CursorHold`, with the special-case that `CursorHold *` only listens to 'updatetime' interval.",
            "created_at": "2026-05-22T08:17:15Z",
